## Why This Is Asked
Tests the ability to design a multi-database write path with explicit keys, TTLs, and idempotency. It also probes cache invalidation strategy and cross-store consistency guarantees.

## Key Concepts
- Polyglot persistence and cross-store dataflow
- Cache invalidation and TTL strategies
- Idempotency keys and deduplication
- Order handling and eventual consistency across stores

## Code Example
```javascript
async function applyProfileUpdate(userId, updates, requestId) {
  // Idempotency guard
  if (await redis.get(`profile:update:${requestId}`)) return;

  // Mark request as processed
  await redis.setex(`profile:update:${requestId}`, 86400, '1');

  const timestamp = Date.now();

  // MongoDB: Update user profile
  await db.users.updateOne(
    { _id: userId, last_modified: { $lte: timestamp } },
    { 
      $set: { 
        ...updates, 
        last_modified: timestamp 
      } 
    }
  );

  // Redis: Invalidate cache
  await Promise.all([
    redis.del(`user:${userId}:profile`),
    redis.del(`session:${userId}:data`)
  ]);

  // Cassandra: Append activity event
  await cassandra.execute(
    `INSERT INTO profile_events (event_id, user_id, event_type, timestamp, data) VALUES (?, ?, 'profile_update', ?, ?)`,
    [requestId, userId, timestamp, updates]
  );

  // DynamoDB: Update search index
  await dynamodb.updateItem({
    TableName: 'user_search_index',
    Key: { user_id: { S: userId } },
    UpdateExpression: 'SET display_name = :dn, bio = :bio, last_modified = :lm',
    ConditionExpression: 'last_modified <= :lm',
    ExpressionAttributeValues: {
      ':dn': { S: updates.display_name },
      ':bio': { S: updates.bio },
      ':lm': { N: timestamp.toString() }
    }
  });
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to craft end-to-end cross-region data flows with idempotence, dedup, and TTL across Redis, DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra. Evaluates data movement, consistency guarantees, and failure handling in distributed systems.

## Key Concepts

- Idempotent writes across stores
- De-duplication using composite keys
- TTL handling in Redis and DynamoDB
- Change data capture across regions (streams)

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudocode: dedupe and propagate fraud signal
async function handleSignal(region, signalId, userId) {
  const dedupKey = `${region}:${signalId}`;
  if (await redis.get(dedupKey)) return;
  await redis.set(dedupKey, '1', { EX: 60 * 60 * 24 });
  // DynamoDB put with conditional to avoid duplicates
  await dynamo.putItem({ id: `${region}#${signalId}`, userId, ts: Date.now() }, { ConditionExpression: 'attribute_not_exists(id)' });
  await cassandra.log({ region, signalId, userId, ts: Date.now() });
  await mongodb.updateOne({ userId }, { $set: { lastFraudAt: new Date() } });
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test fault injection across regions?
- How would you handle late-arriving signals that predate an existing alert?

