## Why This Is Asked
Tests multi-store write coordination, idempotence, and read-path composition across Redis, MongoDB, Cassandra, and DynamoDB in a realistic collaboration app.

## Key Concepts
- Cross-store writes and eventual consistency
- TTL-driven lifecycle for cursors and snapshots
- Idempotence via writeId; conflict resolution with versioning
- Read path assembly from multiple stores

## Code Example
```javascript
// Example schemas (illustrative)
const doc = { docId, version, content, updatedAt }
const cursors = { docId, userId, position }
const events = { docId, version, op, timestamp, writeId }
const snapshots = { docId, snapshotVersion, content, createdAt }

// Multi-store write implementation
async function writeEdit(docId, edit, writeId) {
  // 1. Update MongoDB with version check
  const currentDoc = await MongoDB.findOne({docId})
  if (currentDoc.version !== edit.expectedVersion) {
    throw new Error('Version conflict')
  }

  // 2. Atomic cross-store operations
  await Promise.all([
    MongoDB.updateOne(
      {docId}, 
      {$set: {content: edit.content, version: edit.version, updatedAt: new Date()}}
    ),
    Cassandra.insert({
      docId, 
      version: edit.version, 
      operation: edit.operation, 
      timestamp: new Date(),
      writeId
    }),
    Redis.del(`doc:${docId}:cursors`) // Invalidate cursor cache
  ])

  // 3. Periodic snapshot to DynamoDB (async)
  if (edit.version % 10 === 0) {
    await DynamoDB.put({
      docId,
      snapshotVersion: edit.version,
      content: edit.content,
      createdAt: new Date()
    })
  }
}

// Read path composition
async function readDocument(docId) {
  const [doc, cursors, recentEvents] = await Promise.all([
    MongoDB.findOne({docId}),
    Redis.hgetall(`doc:${docId}:cursors`),
    Cassandra.find({docId}).sort({timestamp: -1}).limit(50)
  ])

  return { doc, cursors, recentEvents }
}
```

## Implementation Notes
- Use writeId for idempotence across all stores
- Implement exponential backoff for cross-store conflicts
- Consider read-repair for eventual consistency scenarios

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design cross-store consistency, idempotent writes, conflict handling, and disaster recovery across polyglot persistence in a real-time collaboration application.

## Key Concepts
- Idempotent multi-store writes across Redis, MongoDB, Cassandra, DynamoDB
- Cross-region conflict handling with eventual consistency
- Replay/restore path and tombstone semantics for recovery

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo: handle save edit across stores with client_write_id
async function saveEdit(doc, delta, clientWriteId) {
  // Redis: cache latest version atomically
  await redis.hSet(`doc:${doc.id}`, {
    content: doc.content,
    version: doc.version,
    clientWriteId
  });

  // MongoDB: upsert with revision tracking
  await db.documents.updateOne(
    { id: doc.id },
    { 
      $set: { 
        content: doc.content,
        version: doc.version,
        updatedAt: new Date(),
        clientWriteId
      }
    },
    { upsert: true }
  );

  // Cassandra: append immutable delta
  await cassandra.execute(
    'INSERT INTO document_edits (doc_id, rev, ts, user, delta, client_write_id) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)',
    [doc.id, doc.version, Date.now(), doc.userId, delta, clientWriteId]
  );

  // DynamoDB: update daily aggregates
  await dynamodb.update({
    TableName: 'daily_aggregates',
    Key: { doc_id: doc.id, date: new Date().toISOString().split('T')[0] },
    UpdateExpression: 'ADD edit_count :inc SET last_edit = :ts',
    ExpressionAttributeValues: { ':inc': 1, ':ts': Date.now() }
  });
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
